const Q_SR_CHEMISTRY=[{"id":"src111001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What are the three main subatomic particles that make up an atom?","options":["protons, electrons, and molecules","protons, neutrons, and electrons","neutrons, ions, and molecules","protons, ions, and ions only"],"answer":1,"exp":"An atom is made up of protons, neutrons, and electrons — protons and neutrons in the nucleus, and electrons orbiting in shells around it."},{"id":"src111002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What determines the atomic number of an element?","options":["the number of neutrons","the number of protons in the nucleus","the number of electrons in the outer shell only","the total mass of the atom"],"answer":1,"exp":"The atomic number is determined by the number of protons in the nucleus, which is unique to each element."},{"id":"src111003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the 'mass number' of an atom?","options":["the number of protons only","the total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus","the number of electrons only","a measure of the atom's overall charge"],"answer":1,"exp":"The mass number is the total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus, representing the approximate mass of the atom."},{"id":"src111004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is an 'isotope'?","options":["an atom with a different number of protons than usual","an atom of the same element with a different number of neutrons, giving it a different mass number","an atom with no electrons","a charged atom or molecule"],"answer":1,"exp":"An isotope is an atom of the same element (same number of protons) but with a different number of neutrons, giving it a different mass number."},{"id":"src111005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"How many electrons can the first electron shell (closest to the nucleus) typically hold?","options":["2","8","18","32"],"answer":0,"exp":"The first electron shell can hold a maximum of 2 electrons."},{"id":"src111006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"How many electrons can the second electron shell typically hold?","options":["2","8","18","32"],"answer":1,"exp":"The second electron shell can hold a maximum of 8 electrons."},{"id":"src111007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the modern periodic table primarily organised by?","options":["atomic mass only, in decreasing order","increasing atomic number, with elements arranged into periods and groups reflecting recurring chemical properties","alphabetical order of element names","the year each element was discovered"],"answer":1,"exp":"The modern periodic table is organised by increasing atomic number, with elements arranged into periods (rows) and groups (columns) that reflect recurring patterns in chemical properties."},{"id":"src111008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What do elements within the same group (column) of the periodic table generally have in common?","options":["an identical atomic mass","a similar number of electrons in their outer shell, giving them similar chemical properties","an identical number of neutrons","no meaningful similarities at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Elements within the same group generally have a similar number of electrons in their outer (valence) shell, which gives them similar chemical properties and reactivity patterns."},{"id":"src111009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"Which group of the periodic table contains the 'noble gases', generally known for their low reactivity?","options":["Group 1","Group 17","Group 18","Group 2"],"answer":2,"exp":"Group 18 contains the noble gases, which generally have a full outer electron shell, making them very stable and largely unreactive."},{"id":"src111010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"Why are Group 1 elements (alkali metals) generally highly reactive?","options":["they have a completely full outer electron shell","they have just one electron in their outer shell, which they readily lose to form a stable, positively charged ion","they have no electrons at all","they are always found as pure elements in nature, never reacting"],"answer":1,"exp":"Group 1 elements have just one electron in their outer shell, which they readily lose to achieve a stable electron configuration, forming a positively charged ion and explaining their high reactivity."},{"id":"src111011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the general trend in atomic radius as you move down a group in the periodic table?","options":["atomic radius generally decreases","atomic radius generally increases, since additional electron shells are added","atomic radius remains exactly constant","atomic radius trends are entirely random with no pattern"],"answer":1,"exp":"Atomic radius generally increases moving down a group, since each successive element has an additional electron shell, increasing the overall size of the atom."},{"id":"src111012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the general trend in atomic radius as you move across a period (row) from left to right?","options":["atomic radius generally increases","atomic radius generally decreases, due to increasing nuclear charge pulling the electrons in more tightly","atomic radius remains exactly constant","there is no general trend across a period"],"answer":1,"exp":"Atomic radius generally decreases moving across a period from left to right, since the increasing nuclear charge (more protons) pulls the electrons in the same shell more tightly toward the nucleus."},{"id":"src111013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is 'electronegativity'?","options":["a measure of an atom's overall mass","a measure of an atom's tendency to attract a shared pair of electrons within a chemical bond","a measure of how many neutrons an atom has","a term unrelated to chemical bonding"],"answer":1,"exp":"Electronegativity is a measure of an atom's tendency to attract a shared pair of electrons within a chemical bond, influencing the type and polarity of bonds it forms."},{"id":"src111014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the general trend in electronegativity as you move across a period from left to right?","options":["electronegativity generally decreases","electronegativity generally increases, as atoms more strongly attract electrons due to increasing nuclear charge","electronegativity remains exactly constant","there is no general trend across a period"],"answer":1,"exp":"Electronegativity generally increases moving across a period from left to right, as atoms with more protons (and thus stronger nuclear charge) attract shared electrons more strongly."},{"id":"src111015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is 'ionisation energy'?","options":["the energy released when an atom gains an electron","the energy required to remove an electron from an atom in its gaseous state","the energy stored within a chemical bond","a term unrelated to atomic structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ionisation energy is the energy required to remove an electron from an atom in its gaseous state, forming a positively charged ion."},{"id":"src111016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the general trend in ionisation energy as you move down a group?","options":["ionisation energy generally increases","ionisation energy generally decreases, since outer electrons are further from the nucleus and more easily removed","ionisation energy remains exactly constant","there is no general trend down a group"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ionisation energy generally decreases moving down a group, since outer electrons are further from the nucleus (in higher shells) and are therefore more easily removed, requiring less energy."},{"id":"src111017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the electron configuration of a neutral sodium atom (atomic number 11)?","options":["2,8,1","2,8,8","2,9","1,8,2"],"answer":0,"exp":"A neutral sodium atom (11 electrons) has the electron configuration 2,8,1 — filling the first shell (2), then the second shell (8), with the remaining 1 electron in the third shell."},{"id":"src111018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is the electron configuration of a neutral chlorine atom (atomic number 17)?","options":["2,8,7","2,8,8","2,7,8","2,15"],"answer":0,"exp":"A neutral chlorine atom (17 electrons) has the electron configuration 2,8,7 — filling the first shell (2), then the second shell (8), with the remaining 7 electrons in the third shell."},{"id":"src111019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"Which subatomic particle has essentially no mass relative to protons and neutrons?","options":["the proton","the neutron","the electron","none of these — all three have equal mass"],"answer":2,"exp":"The electron has essentially negligible mass compared to protons and neutrons, contributing very little to an atom's overall mass."},{"id":"src111020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What charge does a neutron carry?","options":["a positive charge","a negative charge","no charge (neutral)","a variable charge depending on the element"],"answer":2,"exp":"A neutron carries no charge, making it electrically neutral — as its name suggests."},{"id":"src111021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is an 'ion'?","options":["an atom that has gained or lost one or more electrons, giving it an overall electrical charge","an atom with no electrons at all","a synonym for an isotope","a particle found only in the nucleus"],"answer":0,"exp":"An ion is an atom (or molecule) that has gained or lost one or more electrons, giving it an overall positive or negative electrical charge."},{"id":"src111022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is a 'cation'?","options":["a negatively charged ion","a positively charged ion, formed when an atom loses one or more electrons","a neutral atom","a synonym for an isotope"],"answer":1,"exp":"A cation is a positively charged ion, formed when an atom loses one or more electrons."},{"id":"src111023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Atomic Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"What is an 'anion'?","options":["a positively charged ion","a negatively charged ion, formed when an atom gains one or more electrons","a neutral atom","a synonym for a proton"],"answer":1,"exp":"An anion is a negatively charged ion, formed when an atom gains one or more electrons."},{"id":"src111024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"Why do noble gases generally have very low reactivity?","options":["they have no electrons at all","they have a full outer electron shell, making them already very stable and unlikely to gain, lose, or share electrons","they have an unusually high number of protons","noble gases are actually highly reactive, contrary to common description"],"answer":1,"exp":"Noble gases generally have a full outer electron shell, making them already very stable and largely unreactive, since they have little tendency to gain, lose, or share electrons with other atoms."},{"id":"src111025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Periodicity","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C1","q":"Which best describes why elements are arranged into periods (horizontal rows) on the periodic table?","options":["periods have no organisational significance","each period represents the filling of a new outer electron shell, with elements arranged in order of increasing atomic number across that period","periods are arranged purely alphabetically","periods group elements with identical atomic mass only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Each period represents the progressive filling of a new outer electron shell, with elements arranged in order of increasing atomic number from left to right across that period."},{"id":"src112001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is an 'ionic bond'?","options":["a bond formed by sharing electrons equally","a bond formed through the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions, typically between a metal and a non-metal","a bond that only forms between two non-metals","a bond with no real electrical component"],"answer":1,"exp":"An ionic bond forms through the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions, typically occurring between a metal (which loses electrons to form a cation) and a non-metal (which gains electrons to form an anion)."},{"id":"src112002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'covalent bond'?","options":["a bond formed through the transfer of electrons between two ions","a bond formed when two atoms share one or more pairs of electrons","a bond that only occurs in metals","a bond with no connection to electrons at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"A covalent bond forms when two atoms share one or more pairs of electrons, typically occurring between two non-metal atoms."},{"id":"src112003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'metallic bond'?","options":["a bond formed by sharing electrons between two specific atoms","a bond involving a 'sea' of delocalised electrons shared among many metal atoms, giving metals their characteristic properties","a bond that only occurs between a metal and a non-metal","a bond identical to an ionic bond"],"answer":1,"exp":"A metallic bond involves a 'sea' of delocalised electrons shared among many metal atoms, which explains many characteristic metallic properties, such as electrical conductivity and malleability."},{"id":"src112004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why do ionic compounds generally have high melting and boiling points?","options":["ionic bonds are generally very weak","the strong electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions throughout the lattice requires a large amount of energy to overcome","ionic compounds never actually melt","melting point has no connection to bond type"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ionic compounds generally have high melting and boiling points because the strong electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions throughout the entire lattice structure requires a large amount of energy to overcome."},{"id":"src112005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why do ionic compounds conduct electricity when dissolved in water or melted, but not in their solid form?","options":["ionic compounds never conduct electricity in any state","in the solid state, ions are fixed in place within the lattice, but when dissolved or melted, the ions become free to move and carry an electric charge","ionic compounds always conduct electricity in every state","conductivity has no connection to ion mobility"],"answer":1,"exp":"In the solid state, ions are fixed in place within the rigid lattice structure and cannot move freely. When dissolved in water or melted, the ions become free to move, allowing them to carry an electric charge and conduct electricity."},{"id":"src112006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'single covalent bond'?","options":["a bond involving the sharing of one pair of electrons between two atoms","a bond involving the sharing of two pairs of electrons","a bond involving the complete transfer of electrons","a type of ionic bond"],"answer":0,"exp":"A single covalent bond involves the sharing of one pair of electrons between two atoms."},{"id":"src112007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'double covalent bond'?","options":["a bond involving the sharing of one pair of electrons","a bond involving the sharing of two pairs of electrons between two atoms","a bond that is twice as long as a single bond","a synonym for an ionic bond"],"answer":1,"exp":"A double covalent bond involves the sharing of two pairs of electrons between two atoms, generally making the bond shorter and stronger than a single bond."},{"id":"src112008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'polar covalent bond'?","options":["a bond in which electrons are shared completely equally between two atoms","a bond in which electrons are shared unequally between two atoms, due to a difference in electronegativity, creating a partial positive and partial negative charge","a bond that only occurs in metals","a synonym for an ionic bond"],"answer":1,"exp":"A polar covalent bond involves the unequal sharing of electrons between two atoms, due to a difference in electronegativity, creating a partial positive charge on one atom and a partial negative charge on the other."},{"id":"src112009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'non-polar covalent bond'?","options":["a bond between a metal and a non-metal","a bond in which electrons are shared equally (or very nearly so) between two atoms with similar or identical electronegativity","a bond that involves no sharing of electrons at all","a synonym for a metallic bond"],"answer":1,"exp":"A non-polar covalent bond involves electrons shared equally (or very nearly so) between two atoms, typically occurring when the two atoms have similar or identical electronegativity."},{"id":"src112010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Which type of bond would most likely form between sodium (Na) and chlorine (Cl)?","options":["a covalent bond","a metallic bond","an ionic bond, since sodium is a metal and chlorine is a non-metal with a large electronegativity difference","no bond would form at all"],"answer":2,"exp":"An ionic bond would most likely form between sodium and chlorine, since sodium (a metal) readily loses an electron and chlorine (a non-metal) readily gains one, with a large electronegativity difference between them."},{"id":"src112011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Which type of bond would most likely form between two chlorine atoms (Cl₂)?","options":["an ionic bond","a metallic bond","a non-polar covalent bond, since both atoms are identical non-metals with the same electronegativity","no bond would form at all"],"answer":2,"exp":"A non-polar covalent bond would most likely form between two chlorine atoms, since both atoms are identical (and therefore have identical electronegativity), sharing electrons equally."},{"id":"src112012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'lattice structure', as commonly seen in ionic compounds?","options":["a single isolated pair of ions","a repeating, three-dimensional arrangement of oppositely charged ions, extending throughout the solid structure","a structure found only in covalent compounds","a term unrelated to chemical bonding"],"answer":1,"exp":"A lattice structure is a repeating, three-dimensional arrangement of oppositely charged ions, extending throughout the entire solid structure of an ionic compound."},{"id":"src112013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why are metals generally good conductors of electricity?","options":["metals contain no electrons at all","metals contain delocalised electrons that are free to move throughout the metallic structure, allowing them to carry an electric current","metals only conduct electricity when melted","conductivity has no connection to a metal's bonding structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Metals contain delocalised electrons that are free to move throughout the metallic structure, allowing them to carry an electric current, which explains why metals are generally good electrical conductors."},{"id":"src112014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why are metals generally malleable (able to be bent or shaped without breaking)?","options":["metallic bonds are extremely rigid and directional, like covalent bonds","the delocalised electrons allow metal ions to be rearranged or slide past each other without breaking the overall metallic bonding","metals contain no chemical bonds at all","malleability has no connection to bonding structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"The delocalised electrons in metallic bonding allow the metal ions to be rearranged or slide past each other relatively easily, without breaking the overall metallic bonding, which explains why metals are generally malleable."},{"id":"src112015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'molecule'?","options":["a single isolated atom","two or more atoms chemically bonded together, typically through covalent bonds","a synonym for an ion","a structure found only in ionic compounds"],"answer":1,"exp":"A molecule consists of two or more atoms chemically bonded together, typically through covalent bonds, such as a water molecule (H₂O) or an oxygen molecule (O₂)."},{"id":"src112016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Which best describes a 'dative covalent bond' (also called a coordinate bond)?","options":["a bond in which both electrons in the shared pair come from the same atom","a bond formed only between two metals","a bond identical to an ionic bond","a bond that never actually exists in real molecules"],"answer":0,"exp":"A dative covalent (coordinate) bond is a type of covalent bond in which both electrons in the shared pair are donated by the same atom, rather than one from each atom as in a typical covalent bond."},{"id":"src112017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is 'VSEPR theory' (Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion) used to predict?","options":["the colour of a compound","the three-dimensional shape of a molecule, based on the repulsion between electron pairs around a central atom","the melting point of a compound","the conductivity of a metal"],"answer":1,"exp":"VSEPR theory is used to predict the three-dimensional shape of a molecule, based on the principle that electron pairs around a central atom repel each other and arrange themselves to minimise this repulsion."},{"id":"src112018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"According to VSEPR theory, what shape would a molecule with four bonding pairs and no lone pairs around the central atom typically adopt?","options":["linear","trigonal planar","tetrahedral","octahedral"],"answer":2,"exp":"A molecule with four bonding pairs and no lone pairs around the central atom typically adopts a tetrahedral shape, as seen in methane (CH₄)."},{"id":"src112019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why does water (H₂O) have a bent (V-shaped) molecular geometry, rather than a straight line?","options":["water has no lone pairs of electrons on the central oxygen atom","the two lone pairs of electrons on the central oxygen atom repel the bonding pairs, pushing the hydrogen atoms into a bent arrangement","water molecules contain no covalent bonds","molecular geometry has no connection to lone pairs"],"answer":1,"exp":"The two lone pairs of electrons on the central oxygen atom in water repel the bonding pairs (and each other), pushing the two hydrogen atoms into a bent (V-shaped) arrangement, rather than a straight line."},{"id":"src112020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What is a 'hydrogen bond'?","options":["a strong covalent bond between two hydrogen atoms","a relatively weak intermolecular attraction between a hydrogen atom (bonded to a highly electronegative atom) and another highly electronegative atom on a nearby molecule","a bond identical to a typical covalent bond in strength","a bond that only exists within a single isolated molecule"],"answer":1,"exp":"A hydrogen bond is a relatively weak intermolecular attraction between a hydrogen atom (bonded to a highly electronegative atom like oxygen or nitrogen) and another highly electronegative atom on a nearby molecule."},{"id":"src112021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why does water have an unusually high boiling point compared to other molecules of similar size?","options":["water molecules have no intermolecular forces at all","extensive hydrogen bonding between water molecules requires significant energy to overcome, raising the boiling point compared to molecules without this strong intermolecular attraction","water has the lowest boiling point of any molecule its size","boiling point has no connection to intermolecular forces"],"answer":1,"exp":"Extensive hydrogen bonding between water molecules requires significant additional energy to overcome compared to weaker intermolecular forces, which raises water's boiling point notably higher than would be expected for a molecule of its small size."},{"id":"src112022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"What are 'intermolecular forces'?","options":["the forces holding atoms together within a single molecule","the forces of attraction that exist between separate molecules","a synonym for ionic bonds","forces that only exist within metals"],"answer":1,"exp":"Intermolecular forces are the forces of attraction that exist between separate molecules, distinct from the (generally much stronger) intramolecular bonds holding atoms together within a single molecule."},{"id":"src112023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Which type of intermolecular force is generally the weakest, occurring even between non-polar molecules?","options":["hydrogen bonding","ionic bonding","London dispersion forces (a type of van der Waals force)","covalent bonding"],"answer":2,"exp":"London dispersion forces (a type of van der Waals force) are generally the weakest intermolecular force, arising from temporary fluctuations in electron distribution, and occur even between non-polar molecules."},{"id":"src112024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Why do larger molecules generally experience stronger London dispersion forces than smaller molecules?","options":["molecule size has no connection to the strength of these forces","larger molecules generally have more electrons, creating a greater potential for temporary, fluctuating charge distributions that increase the overall attractive force","smaller molecules always have stronger London dispersion forces","London dispersion forces only occur in ionic compounds"],"answer":1,"exp":"Larger molecules generally have more electrons, creating a greater potential for temporary, fluctuating charge distributions (instantaneous dipoles), which increases the overall strength of the London dispersion forces between them."},{"id":"src112025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Chemical Bonding","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C2","q":"Which best describes a 'coordinate (dative) covalent bond'?","options":["a bond where both atoms contribute one electron each, as in a typical covalent bond","a bond where both bonding electrons are donated by just one of the two atoms involved","a bond formed only between two metal atoms","a bond that exists only in ionic compounds"],"answer":1,"exp":"A coordinate (dative) covalent bond forms when both bonding electrons are donated by just one of the two atoms involved, such as in the ammonium ion (NH₄⁺), unlike a typical covalent bond where each atom contributes one electron."},{"id":"src113001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the molar mass of water (H₂O)? (H = 1 g/mol, O = 16 g/mol)","options":["16 g/mol","17 g/mol","18 g/mol","20 g/mol"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Molar mass = (2 × 1) + 16. Step 2: 2 + 16 = 18 g/mol."},{"id":"src113002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the molar mass of carbon dioxide (CO₂)? (C = 12 g/mol, O = 16 g/mol)","options":["28 g/mol","32 g/mol","44 g/mol","48 g/mol"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Molar mass = 12 + (2 × 16). Step 2: 12 + 32 = 44 g/mol."},{"id":"src113003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the molar mass of sodium chloride (NaCl)? (Na = 23 g/mol, Cl = 35.5 g/mol)","options":["46 g/mol","52.5 g/mol","58.5 g/mol","61 g/mol"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Molar mass = 23 + 35.5. Step 2: This gives 58.5 g/mol."},{"id":"src113004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"How many moles are in 18 g of water? (molar mass of H₂O = 18 g/mol)","options":["0.5 mol","1 mol","2 mol","18 mol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Moles = mass ÷ molar mass. Step 2: 18 ÷ 18 = 1 mol."},{"id":"src113005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the mass of 2 moles of sodium chloride (NaCl), given a molar mass of 58.5 g/mol?","options":["29.25 g","58.5 g","117 g","234 g"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Mass = moles × molar mass. Step 2: 2 × 58.5 = 117 g."},{"id":"src113006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Avogadro's Number","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"How many particles (atoms or molecules) are in 2 moles of a substance, using Avogadro's number (6.022 × 10²³)?","options":["3.011 × 10²³","6.022 × 10²³","1.2044 × 10²⁴","1.2044 × 10²³"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Number of particles = moles × Avogadro's number. Step 2: 2 × 6.022 × 10²³ = 1.2044 × 10²⁴."},{"id":"src113007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Concentration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the concentration (in mol/L) of a solution containing 0.5 mol of solute dissolved in 2 L of solution?","options":["0.25 mol/L","0.5 mol/L","1 mol/L","2.5 mol/L"],"answer":0,"exp":"Step 1: Concentration = moles ÷ volume (in litres). Step 2: 0.5 ÷ 2 = 0.25 mol/L."},{"id":"src113008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Concentration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"How many moles of solute are in 0.5 L of a 2 mol/L solution?","options":["0.25 mol","1 mol","2 mol","4 mol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Moles = concentration × volume (in litres). Step 2: 2 × 0.5 = 1 mol."},{"id":"src113009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Limiting Reagent","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"In the reaction 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, if 4 mol of H₂ reacts with 1 mol of O₂, which reactant is the limiting reagent?","options":["H₂, because it runs out first","O₂, because only 2 mol of H₂ is actually needed to react with 1 mol O₂, leaving H₂ in excess","neither reactant is limiting","both reactants run out at exactly the same time"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: The equation shows 1 mol O₂ requires 2 mol H₂. Step 2: With 1 mol O₂ available, only 2 mol H₂ is needed, but 4 mol H₂ is present, leaving H₂ in excess. Step 3: O₂ is therefore the limiting reagent."},{"id":"src113010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"In the reaction 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, if O₂ is the limiting reagent and 1 mol of O₂ is fully consumed, how many moles of H₂O are produced?","options":["0.5 mol","1 mol","2 mol","4 mol"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: The equation shows a 1:2 ratio between O₂ and H₂O. Step 2: 1 mol O₂ produces 2 mol H₂O."},{"id":"src113011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Percentage Yield","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"A reaction has a theoretical yield of 5 g, but the actual yield obtained is 3.5 g. What is the percentage yield?","options":["35%","50%","70%","75%"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Percentage yield = (actual yield ÷ theoretical yield) × 100. Step 2: (3.5 ÷ 5) × 100 = 70%."},{"id":"src113012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the molar mass of calcium carbonate (CaCO₃)? (Ca = 40 g/mol, C = 12 g/mol, O = 16 g/mol)","options":["68 g/mol","84 g/mol","100 g/mol","116 g/mol"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Molar mass = 40 + 12 + (3 × 16). Step 2: 40 + 12 + 48 = 100 g/mol."},{"id":"src113013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Gas Volumes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"At standard temperature and pressure (STP, using a molar volume of 22.7 L/mol), what is the volume of 2 moles of an ideal gas?","options":["11.35 L","22.7 L","45.4 L","68.1 L"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Volume = moles × molar volume. Step 2: 2 × 22.7 = 45.4 L."},{"id":"src113014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Gas Volumes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"How many moles of gas occupy 11.35 L at STP, using a molar volume of 22.7 L/mol?","options":["0.25 mol","0.5 mol","1 mol","2 mol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Moles = volume ÷ molar volume. Step 2: 11.35 ÷ 22.7 = 0.5 mol."},{"id":"src113015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Percentage Composition","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the percentage composition of carbon in carbon dioxide (CO₂)? (molar mass CO₂ = 44 g/mol, C = 12 g/mol)","options":["12%","27.3%","36.4%","50%"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Percentage = (mass of element ÷ total molar mass) × 100. Step 2: (12 ÷ 44) × 100 ≈ 27.3%."},{"id":"src113016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Empirical Formula","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is an 'empirical formula' in chemistry?","options":["the formula showing the actual total number of atoms in a molecule","the simplest whole-number ratio of atoms of each element in a compound","a formula used only for ionic compounds","a formula that shows only the molecular mass"],"answer":1,"exp":"An empirical formula shows the simplest whole-number ratio of atoms of each element in a compound, which may differ from the actual molecular formula."},{"id":"src113017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Molecular Formula","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"A compound has the empirical formula CH₂O and a molecular mass of 180 g/mol. Given the empirical formula mass is 30 g/mol, what is the molecular formula?","options":["CH₂O","C₃H₆O₃","C₆H₁₂O₆","C₉H₁₈O₉"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Divide molecular mass by empirical formula mass: 180 ÷ 30 = 6. Step 2: Multiply each subscript in the empirical formula by 6: C₆H₁₂O₆."},{"id":"src113018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"How many moles of NaOH are needed to fully neutralise 2 mol of HCl, given the equation NaOH + HCl → NaCl + H₂O?","options":["1 mol","2 mol","3 mol","4 mol"],"answer":1,"exp":"The balanced equation shows a 1:1 ratio between NaOH and HCl, so 2 mol of HCl requires 2 mol of NaOH for complete neutralisation."},{"id":"src113019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Concentration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What volume (in mL) of a 2 mol/L solution would contain exactly 0.4 mol of solute?","options":["100 mL","200 mL","400 mL","800 mL"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Volume (L) = moles ÷ concentration = 0.4 ÷ 2 = 0.2 L. Step 2: Convert to mL: 0.2 × 1000 = 200 mL."},{"id":"src113020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Dilution","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"A solution is diluted from 100 mL of 4 mol/L stock solution to a final volume of 400 mL. What is the new concentration?","options":["0.5 mol/L","1 mol/L","2 mol/L","4 mol/L"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Use the dilution formula: C₁V₁ = C₂V₂. Step 2: 4 × 100 = C₂ × 400. Step 3: C₂ = 400 ÷ 400 = 1 mol/L."},{"id":"src113021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the molar mass of glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆)? (C = 12 g/mol, H = 1 g/mol, O = 16 g/mol)","options":["150 g/mol","162 g/mol","180 g/mol","192 g/mol"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Molar mass = (6×12) + (12×1) + (6×16). Step 2: 72 + 12 + 96 = 180 g/mol."},{"id":"src113022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Concentration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"If 5.85 g of NaCl is dissolved to make 250 mL of solution, what is the concentration? (molar mass NaCl = 58.5 g/mol)","options":["0.1 mol/L","0.2 mol/L","0.4 mol/L","0.5 mol/L"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Moles = mass ÷ molar mass = 5.85 ÷ 58.5 = 0.1 mol. Step 2: Concentration = moles ÷ volume (L) = 0.1 ÷ 0.25 = 0.4 mol/L."},{"id":"src113023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"Which best describes why chemists use the mole as a unit, rather than counting individual atoms or molecules directly?","options":["atoms and molecules are too large to count individually","the mole provides a practical, convenient way to relate the vast numbers of particles in a sample to measurable quantities like mass","the mole is simply a historical convention with no practical purpose","atoms cannot actually be counted using any unit"],"answer":1,"exp":"The mole provides a practical, convenient way to relate the vast numbers of atoms or molecules in a sample (far too many to count individually) to measurable quantities like mass, via Avogadro's number."},{"id":"src113024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"A reaction produces 8.8 g of CO₂. How many moles of CO₂ does this represent? (molar mass CO₂ = 44 g/mol)","options":["0.1 mol","0.2 mol","0.4 mol","0.8 mol"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Moles = mass ÷ molar mass. Step 2: 8.8 ÷ 44 = 0.2 mol."},{"id":"src113025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Stoichiometry — Percentage Composition","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C3","q":"What is the percentage composition of hydrogen in water (H₂O)? (molar mass H₂O = 18 g/mol, H = 1 g/mol)","options":["5.6%","11.1%","16.7%","20%"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Mass contributed by hydrogen = 2 × 1 = 2 g/mol. Step 2: Percentage = (2 ÷ 18) × 100 ≈ 11.1%."},{"id":"src114001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Boyle's Law","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"A gas occupies 2 L at a pressure of 100 kPa. Using Boyle's Law (P₁V₁ = P₂V₂), what volume would it occupy at 200 kPa, assuming constant temperature?","options":["0.5 L","1 L","2 L","4 L"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: P₁V₁ = P₂V₂, so 100 × 2 = 200 × V₂. Step 2: V₂ = 200 ÷ 200 = 1 L."},{"id":"src114002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Boyle's Law","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"A gas occupies 6 L at 300 kPa. Using Boyle's Law, what pressure would be needed to compress it to 2 L, at constant temperature?","options":["100 kPa","450 kPa","600 kPa","900 kPa"],"answer":3,"exp":"Step 1: P₁V₁ = P₂V₂, so 300 × 6 = P₂ × 2. Step 2: P₂ = 1800 ÷ 2 = 900 kPa."},{"id":"src114003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Charles's Law","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"A gas occupies 2 L at 300 K. Using Charles's Law (V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂), what volume would it occupy at 600 K, at constant pressure?","options":["1 L","2 L","4 L","6 L"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂, so 2/300 = V₂/600. Step 2: V₂ = 2 × (600/300) = 4 L."},{"id":"src114004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Charles's Law","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"A gas occupies 8 L at 400 K. Using Charles's Law, what would its volume be at 200 K, at constant pressure?","options":["2 L","4 L","16 L","32 L"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂, so 8/400 = V₂/200. Step 2: V₂ = 8 × (200/400) = 4 L."},{"id":"src114005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Why must temperature be expressed in Kelvin (not Celsius) when applying gas laws like Charles's Law?","options":["Kelvin is simply a more modern unit with no mathematical significance","gas law equations involve direct proportionality with temperature, which only holds true using an absolute temperature scale starting at absolute zero","Celsius cannot be converted into any other unit","gas laws do not actually require any particular temperature unit"],"answer":1,"exp":"Gas law equations rely on direct proportionality with temperature, which only holds true using an absolute temperature scale (Kelvin) that starts at absolute zero — using Celsius (which has an arbitrary zero point) would give incorrect ratios."},{"id":"src114006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Ideal Gas Law","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes what the ideal gas law (PV = nRT) relates?","options":["only the pressure and volume of a gas, with no other variables","the pressure, volume, number of moles, and temperature of a gas, assuming ideal behaviour","only the temperature and number of moles of a gas","the density and colour of a gas"],"answer":1,"exp":"The ideal gas law relates the pressure (P), volume (V), number of moles (n), and temperature (T) of a gas, assuming the gas behaves ideally."},{"id":"src114007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Gas Laws — Real Gases","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Under which conditions do real gases tend to deviate most significantly from ideal gas behaviour?","options":["at low pressure and high temperature","at high pressure and low temperature, where intermolecular forces and particle volume become more significant","real gases never deviate from ideal behaviour under any conditions","only at exactly room temperature and atmospheric pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Real gases deviate most significantly from ideal behaviour at high pressure and low temperature, where intermolecular forces and the actual volume of gas particles become more significant relative to the assumptions of the ideal gas model."},{"id":"src114008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes a 'saturated solution'?","options":["a solution containing no solute at all","a solution that has dissolved the maximum amount of solute possible at a given temperature","a solution that is always coloured","a solution that has dissolved too much solute and become unstable"],"answer":1,"exp":"A saturated solution has dissolved the maximum amount of solute possible at a given temperature, with any additional solute unable to dissolve further under those conditions."},{"id":"src114009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes a 'supersaturated solution'?","options":["a solution containing less solute than a saturated solution","a solution containing more dissolved solute than would normally be possible at that temperature, often in an unstable state","a solution with no solute dissolved at all","a synonym for a dilute solution"],"answer":1,"exp":"A supersaturated solution contains more dissolved solute than would normally be possible at that temperature, existing in an unstable state that can rapidly crystallise if disturbed."},{"id":"src114010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions — Solubility","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"How does increasing temperature generally affect the solubility of most solid solutes in water?","options":["it generally decreases solubility","it generally increases solubility, as increased thermal energy helps break apart the solute's structure and disperse particles","temperature has no effect on solid solubility","all solids become completely insoluble at higher temperatures"],"answer":1,"exp":"Increasing temperature generally increases the solubility of most solid solutes in water, as the increased thermal energy helps overcome the forces holding the solute's structure together, allowing particles to disperse into the solvent."},{"id":"src114011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions — Solubility","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"How does increasing temperature generally affect the solubility of gases in water?","options":["it generally increases gas solubility","it generally decreases gas solubility, as gas particles gain enough energy to escape the solution more easily","temperature has no effect on gas solubility","all gases become completely soluble at higher temperatures"],"answer":1,"exp":"Increasing temperature generally decreases the solubility of gases in water, as gas particles gain enough kinetic energy to escape the solution more easily, which is why warm soft drinks lose their fizz faster than cold ones."},{"id":"src114012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions — Solubility","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"How does increasing pressure generally affect the solubility of a gas in a liquid?","options":["it generally decreases gas solubility","it generally increases gas solubility, as described qualitatively by Henry's Law","pressure has no effect on gas solubility","it only affects solid solubility, not gas solubility"],"answer":1,"exp":"Increasing pressure generally increases the solubility of a gas in a liquid, a relationship qualitatively described by Henry's Law, which is why carbonated drinks are bottled under pressure."},{"id":"src114013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions — Solubility","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes the principle 'like dissolves like' in the context of solubility?","options":["solutes only dissolve in solvents of an identical chemical formula","polar solvents tend to dissolve polar (or ionic) solutes well, while non-polar solvents tend to dissolve non-polar solutes well","all substances are equally soluble in all solvents","this principle has no real basis in chemistry"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Like dissolves like\" describes how polar solvents (such as water) tend to dissolve polar or ionic solutes well, while non-polar solvents tend to dissolve non-polar solutes well, due to the compatibility of intermolecular forces involved."},{"id":"src114014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Why does sodium chloride (an ionic compound) dissolve readily in water?","options":["water has no real interaction with ionic compounds","water's polar molecules surround and stabilise the separated Na⁺ and Cl⁻ ions, a process called hydration","sodium chloride is actually non-polar","ionic compounds never dissolve in any solvent"],"answer":1,"exp":"Water's polar molecules surround and stabilise the separated Na⁺ and Cl⁻ ions (a process called hydration), with the positive ends of water molecules attracted to Cl⁻ and the negative ends attracted to Na⁺."},{"id":"src114015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter — Intermolecular Forces","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best explains why substances with stronger intermolecular forces generally have higher boiling points?","options":["intermolecular force strength has no connection to boiling point","more energy is required to overcome stronger intermolecular forces and separate particles into the gas phase","stronger intermolecular forces always lower the boiling point","boiling point is determined only by molecular mass, not intermolecular forces"],"answer":1,"exp":"Boiling requires overcoming the intermolecular forces holding particles together in the liquid phase. Stronger intermolecular forces require more energy (and thus a higher temperature) to overcome, resulting in a higher boiling point."},{"id":"src114016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter — Intermolecular Forces","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which of these substances would be expected to have the highest boiling point, based on intermolecular forces?","options":["a substance with only weak London dispersion forces","a substance with dipole-dipole forces","a substance with hydrogen bonding","a substance with no intermolecular forces at all"],"answer":2,"exp":"Hydrogen bonding is generally the strongest of the common intermolecular forces (stronger than dipole-dipole or London dispersion forces alone), so a substance exhibiting hydrogen bonding would typically have the highest boiling point among these options."},{"id":"src114017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter — Intermolecular Forces","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Why does water have an unusually high boiling point compared to other small molecules of similar molar mass?","options":["water has no intermolecular forces at all","water molecules form hydrogen bonds with each other, which are relatively strong and require significant energy to overcome","water is actually an unusually small molecule with no special properties","boiling point is unrelated to molecular structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Water molecules form hydrogen bonds with each other (due to the highly electronegative oxygen atom bonded to hydrogen), which are relatively strong intermolecular forces requiring significant energy to overcome, giving water an unusually high boiling point for its small molar mass."},{"id":"src114018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"What is 'vapour pressure' in the context of a liquid?","options":["the pressure exerted by a liquid's solid form","the pressure exerted by the vapour of a liquid in equilibrium with that liquid at a given temperature","a measurement that only applies to gases, not liquids","a fixed property unrelated to temperature"],"answer":1,"exp":"Vapour pressure is the pressure exerted by the vapour (gas) of a liquid when it is in equilibrium with that liquid at a given temperature, reflecting the tendency of liquid molecules to escape into the gas phase."},{"id":"src114019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"How does increasing temperature generally affect a liquid's vapour pressure?","options":["it generally decreases vapour pressure","it generally increases vapour pressure, as more molecules gain enough energy to escape into the vapour phase","temperature has no effect on vapour pressure","vapour pressure only depends on atmospheric pressure, not temperature"],"answer":1,"exp":"Increasing temperature generally increases a liquid's vapour pressure, as more molecules gain sufficient kinetic energy to escape from the liquid into the vapour phase."},{"id":"src114020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"A liquid boils when its vapour pressure equals which of these?","options":["the liquid's freezing point","the surrounding atmospheric pressure","absolute zero","the liquid's molar mass"],"answer":1,"exp":"A liquid boils when its vapour pressure becomes equal to the surrounding atmospheric pressure, allowing bubbles of vapour to form within the liquid itself."},{"id":"src114021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Why does water boil at a lower temperature at high altitude, where atmospheric pressure is lower?","options":["high altitude has no effect on boiling point","a lower atmospheric pressure means the water's vapour pressure reaches that lower value at a lower temperature","water freezes faster at high altitude, preventing it from boiling normally","boiling point is completely unrelated to atmospheric pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Since boiling occurs when vapour pressure equals atmospheric pressure, a lower atmospheric pressure at high altitude means the water's vapour pressure reaches that (lower) value at a correspondingly lower temperature."},{"id":"src114022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes 'viscosity' as a property of liquids?","options":["a measure of a liquid's colour intensity","a measure of a liquid's resistance to flow, related to the strength of intermolecular forces and molecular shape","a measure of a liquid's boiling point only","a property that applies only to gases"],"answer":1,"exp":"Viscosity is a measure of a liquid's resistance to flow, generally related to the strength of intermolecular forces between its particles and the shape/size of its molecules."},{"id":"src114023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best explains why long-chain molecules tend to have higher viscosity than short-chain molecules of a similar type?","options":["chain length has no effect on viscosity","longer chains can become more entangled and experience greater cumulative intermolecular attraction, increasing resistance to flow","longer chains always have weaker intermolecular forces","shorter chains always have higher viscosity than longer ones"],"answer":1,"exp":"Longer molecular chains can become more entangled with each other and experience greater cumulative intermolecular attraction along their length, increasing the liquid's overall resistance to flow (viscosity)."},{"id":"src114024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"States of Matter","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes 'surface tension' in a liquid?","options":["a property only found in solids","the tendency of a liquid's surface to behave like a stretched elastic film, due to cohesive forces between surface molecules","a measure of a liquid's boiling point","a property unrelated to intermolecular forces"],"answer":1,"exp":"Surface tension is the tendency of a liquid's surface to behave like a stretched elastic film, caused by cohesive intermolecular forces pulling surface molecules inward and toward each other."},{"id":"src114025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"11","topic":"Solutions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G11-C4","q":"Which best describes how dissolving a solute generally affects a solvent's boiling point?","options":["dissolving a solute has no effect on boiling point","dissolving a solute generally raises the solvent's boiling point, an effect known as boiling point elevation","dissolving a solute always lowers the boiling point","boiling point elevation only occurs with gaseous solutes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Dissolving a solute generally raises a solvent's boiling point, an effect known as boiling point elevation, because the dissolved particles disrupt the solvent's ability to escape into the vapour phase as easily."},{"id":"src121001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Alkanes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What is the general formula for an alkane with n carbon atoms?","options":["CₙH₂ₙ","CₙH₂ₙ₊₂","CₙH₂ₙ₋₂","CₙHₙ"],"answer":1,"exp":"Alkanes are saturated hydrocarbons with the general formula CₙH₂ₙ₊₂, containing only single bonds between carbon atoms."},{"id":"src121002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Alkanes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What is the molecular formula of propane, an alkane with 3 carbon atoms?","options":["C₃H₆","C₃H₈","C₃H₄","C₃H₁₀"],"answer":1,"exp":"Using the alkane formula CₙH₂ₙ₊₂ with n=3: C₃H₈ (3×2+2=8 hydrogen atoms)."},{"id":"src121003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Alkenes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What distinguishes an alkene from an alkane?","options":["alkenes contain only single bonds, like alkanes","alkenes contain at least one carbon-carbon double bond, making them unsaturated","alkenes always contain more carbon atoms than alkanes","there is no real difference between alkenes and alkanes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Alkenes contain at least one carbon-carbon double bond, making them unsaturated hydrocarbons, unlike alkanes which contain only single bonds."},{"id":"src121004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Alkenes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What is the general formula for an alkene with one double bond and n carbon atoms?","options":["CₙH₂ₙ₊₂","CₙH₂ₙ","CₙH₂ₙ₋₂","CₙH₂ₙ₊₁"],"answer":1,"exp":"Alkenes with one double bond follow the general formula CₙH₂ₙ, having two fewer hydrogen atoms than the corresponding alkane."},{"id":"src121005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Functional Groups","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which functional group characterises an alcohol?","options":["-COOH","-OH","-CHO","-NH₂"],"answer":1,"exp":"The hydroxyl group (-OH) characterises alcohols, such as ethanol (C₂H₅OH)."},{"id":"src121006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Functional Groups","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which functional group characterises a carboxylic acid?","options":["-OH","-COOH","-CHO","-NH₂"],"answer":1,"exp":"The carboxyl group (-COOH) characterises carboxylic acids, such as acetic acid (CH₃COOH)."},{"id":"src121007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Functional Groups","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which functional group characterises an amine?","options":["-OH","-COOH","-NH₂","-CHO"],"answer":2,"exp":"The amine group (-NH₂) characterises amines, which are derivatives of ammonia where one or more hydrogen atoms are replaced by carbon-containing groups."},{"id":"src121008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What type of reaction occurs when an alcohol reacts with a carboxylic acid to form an ester?","options":["combustion","esterification (a condensation reaction)","polymerisation","oxidation only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Esterification is a condensation reaction between an alcohol and a carboxylic acid, producing an ester and water."},{"id":"src121009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What are the products of esterification between an alcohol and a carboxylic acid?","options":["an ester and water","an alkane and oxygen","an alkene and hydrogen","an amine and carbon dioxide"],"answer":0,"exp":"Esterification produces an ester and water, as the carboxylic acid's -OH group combines with a hydrogen from the alcohol's -OH group."},{"id":"src121010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Isomers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What is a 'structural isomer'?","options":["a molecule with the same molecular formula but a different arrangement of atoms","two completely different compounds with no relationship at all","a molecule that has been ionised","a synonym for a functional group"],"answer":0,"exp":"Structural isomers share the same molecular formula but have a different arrangement (structure) of atoms, often resulting in different chemical and physical properties."},{"id":"src121011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Isomers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Butane (C₄H₁₀) has a structural isomer called 2-methylpropane. What does this tell you about these two molecules?","options":["they have completely different molecular formulas","they share the same molecular formula but have different structural arrangements of their carbon atoms","they are actually the same molecule with two different names","one of them is not actually a real hydrocarbon"],"answer":1,"exp":"Both butane and 2-methylpropane share the molecular formula C₄H₁₀, but have different structural arrangements — butane has a straight chain, while 2-methylpropane has a branched structure."},{"id":"src121012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Polymers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What type of polymerisation occurs when alkene monomers join together by opening their double bonds, with no other molecule released?","options":["condensation polymerisation","addition polymerisation","esterification","combustion"],"answer":1,"exp":"Addition polymerisation occurs when monomers (often alkenes) join together by opening their double bonds, with no other molecule released as a by-product, forming a long-chain polymer."},{"id":"src121013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Polymers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes 'condensation polymerisation'?","options":["monomers join together with no other molecule released","monomers join together with the release of a small molecule, such as water, at each linkage","a process that never occurs in nature","a synonym for addition polymerisation"],"answer":1,"exp":"Condensation polymerisation occurs when monomers join together with the release of a small molecule (often water) at each linkage point, as seen in the formation of proteins and some synthetic polymers like nylon."},{"id":"src121014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Combustion","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes complete combustion of a hydrocarbon in excess oxygen?","options":["it produces carbon monoxide and water","it produces carbon dioxide and water, releasing energy","it produces only carbon and hydrogen gas","combustion never produces any energy"],"answer":1,"exp":"Complete combustion of a hydrocarbon in excess oxygen produces carbon dioxide and water, releasing energy as heat and light."},{"id":"src121015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Combustion","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What is produced during incomplete combustion of a hydrocarbon, due to insufficient oxygen?","options":["only carbon dioxide and water, identical to complete combustion","carbon monoxide and/or soot (carbon), along with water","pure oxygen gas","no products are formed at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Incomplete combustion, occurring with insufficient oxygen, produces carbon monoxide and/or soot (unburned carbon), along with water, rather than fully oxidising all the carbon to carbon dioxide."},{"id":"src121016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Combustion","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Why is carbon monoxide produced by incomplete combustion considered dangerous?","options":["it is harmless and has no health effects","it binds to haemoglobin in blood more strongly than oxygen, reducing the blood's ability to carry oxygen around the body","it is simply an unpleasant smell with no health risk","carbon monoxide is identical to carbon dioxide"],"answer":1,"exp":"Carbon monoxide binds to haemoglobin in the blood more strongly than oxygen does, reducing the blood's capacity to carry oxygen around the body, which can be dangerous or even fatal in sufficient concentrations."},{"id":"src121017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes 'addition reactions' involving alkenes, such as reacting with hydrogen (hydrogenation)?","options":["the double bond remains unchanged while new atoms are added elsewhere","the double bond opens up, allowing new atoms to bond to the previously double-bonded carbons","alkenes cannot undergo any addition reactions","addition reactions always release a small molecule like water"],"answer":1,"exp":"In an addition reaction, the carbon-carbon double bond opens up, allowing new atoms (such as hydrogen in hydrogenation) to bond directly to the two carbons that were previously double-bonded."},{"id":"src121018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"What product forms when ethene (C₂H₄) undergoes hydrogenation (addition of H₂)?","options":["ethane (C₂H₆)","ethanol (C₂H₅OH)","ethanoic acid (CH₃COOH)","methane (CH₄)"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hydrogenation adds H₂ across the double bond of ethene, converting it into the saturated alkane ethane (C₂H₆)."},{"id":"src121019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes a 'homologous series' in organic chemistry?","options":["a group of compounds with completely unrelated chemical properties","a series of compounds with the same general formula and similar chemical properties, differing by a repeating unit (such as -CH₂-)","a single specific compound with multiple names","a synonym for an isomer"],"answer":1,"exp":"A homologous series is a group of compounds with the same general formula and similar chemical properties, with each successive member differing by a repeating structural unit, typically -CH₂-."},{"id":"src121020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Properties","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Why do larger alkane molecules generally have higher boiling points than smaller ones within the same homologous series?","options":["larger molecules have weaker intermolecular forces","larger molecules have a greater surface area, leading to stronger cumulative London dispersion forces between molecules","molecular size has no effect on boiling point","larger alkanes are always gases at room temperature"],"answer":1,"exp":"Larger alkane molecules have a greater surface area, leading to stronger cumulative London dispersion forces between molecules, which require more energy to overcome, resulting in higher boiling points."},{"id":"src121021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes the difference between a 'saturated' and an 'unsaturated' hydrocarbon?","options":["saturated hydrocarbons contain double or triple bonds, while unsaturated ones do not","saturated hydrocarbons contain only single bonds, while unsaturated hydrocarbons contain at least one double or triple bond","there is no real difference between these terms","unsaturated hydrocarbons cannot exist in nature"],"answer":1,"exp":"Saturated hydrocarbons (alkanes) contain only single bonds between carbon atoms, while unsaturated hydrocarbons (such as alkenes and alkynes) contain at least one double or triple bond."},{"id":"src121022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Testing","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Bromine water can be used to test for the presence of a carbon-carbon double bond. What colour change indicates a positive result (the presence of an alkene)?","options":["the bromine water turns from colourless to orange","the bromine water turns from orange/brown to colourless","the bromine water turns blue","no colour change occurs with either alkanes or alkenes"],"answer":1,"exp":"When bromine water reacts with an alkene's double bond (in an addition reaction), it turns from orange/brown to colourless, providing a simple test for unsaturation. Alkanes, lacking double bonds, do not produce this colour change."},{"id":"src121023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Properties","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes why ethanol (a small alcohol) is soluble in water, while larger alcohols become progressively less soluble?","options":["alcohols are never soluble in water under any circumstances","the -OH group can hydrogen bond with water, but as the non-polar hydrocarbon chain grows longer, it increasingly dominates the molecule's overall behaviour, reducing solubility","alcohol solubility has no connection to molecular structure","all alcohols are equally soluble regardless of size"],"answer":1,"exp":"The -OH group can hydrogen bond with water, supporting solubility, but as the non-polar hydrocarbon chain grows longer in larger alcohols, this non-polar portion increasingly dominates the molecule's overall behaviour, reducing its solubility in water."},{"id":"src121024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Which best describes the role of a catalyst, such as in the catalytic cracking of long-chain hydrocarbons into shorter, more useful ones?","options":["catalysts are consumed during the reaction and must be continually replaced","a catalyst speeds up a reaction by lowering the activation energy, without being consumed in the overall process","catalysts always slow down chemical reactions","catalysts change the products of a reaction, not just its rate"],"answer":1,"exp":"A catalyst speeds up a reaction, such as the cracking of long-chain hydrocarbons, by lowering the activation energy required, without being consumed or permanently altered in the overall process."},{"id":"src121025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Organic Chemistry — Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C1","q":"Why is 'cracking' (breaking long-chain hydrocarbons into shorter ones) an economically important industrial process?","options":["it has no real industrial value","shorter-chain hydrocarbons, like petrol, are in much higher demand than the longer chains naturally present in larger quantities in crude oil","cracking only produces waste products with no use","longer-chain hydrocarbons are always more valuable than shorter ones"],"answer":1,"exp":"Cracking is economically important because shorter-chain hydrocarbons, such as petrol, are in much higher demand than the longer-chain hydrocarbons that are naturally more abundant in crude oil, allowing refineries to convert excess long chains into more valuable shorter ones."},{"id":"src122001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"What is meant by 'dynamic equilibrium' in a reversible chemical reaction?","options":["the reaction has completely stopped","the forward and reverse reactions continue to occur, but at equal rates, so concentrations of reactants and products remain constant","only the forward reaction occurs at equilibrium","equilibrium means all reactants have been converted to products"],"answer":1,"exp":"Dynamic equilibrium occurs when the forward and reverse reactions continue to occur simultaneously, but at equal rates, so that the concentrations of reactants and products remain constant over time (though not necessarily equal to each other)."},{"id":"src122002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For the reaction A + B ⇌ C + D, if [A]=2 mol/L, [B]=1 mol/L, [C]=4 mol/L, and [D]=2 mol/L at equilibrium, what is the equilibrium constant Kc?","options":["1","2","4","8"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Kc = [C][D] ÷ [A][B]. Step 2: (4 × 2) ÷ (2 × 1) = 8 ÷ 2 = 4."},{"id":"src122003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For the reaction 2A ⇌ B, if [A]=0.5 mol/L and [B]=2 mol/L at equilibrium, what is Kc?","options":["1","4","8","16"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Kc = [B] ÷ [A]². Step 2: 2 ÷ (0.5)² = 2 ÷ 0.25 = 8."},{"id":"src122004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"What does a very large value of Kc (much greater than 1) generally indicate about a reaction at equilibrium?","options":["the reaction strongly favours the reactants","the reaction strongly favours the products, meaning at equilibrium most of the reactants have been converted into products","the reaction has not actually reached equilibrium","Kc values have no relationship to the position of equilibrium"],"answer":1,"exp":"A very large Kc value indicates that, at equilibrium, the concentration of products is much greater than the concentration of reactants, meaning the reaction strongly favours the products."},{"id":"src122005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"What does Le Chatelier's Principle state about a system at equilibrium when subjected to a change in conditions?","options":["the system will remain completely unaffected by any change","the system will shift in a direction that partially counteracts the change, re-establishing a new equilibrium","the system will always shift to favour the reactants, regardless of the change","equilibrium can never be re-established once disturbed"],"answer":1,"exp":"Le Chatelier's Principle states that when a system at equilibrium is subjected to a change in conditions (such as concentration, temperature, or pressure), the system will shift in a direction that partially counteracts that change, establishing a new equilibrium position."},{"id":"src122006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"According to Le Chatelier's Principle, what happens to an equilibrium if the concentration of a reactant is increased?","options":["the equilibrium shifts toward the reactants","the equilibrium shifts toward the products, partially consuming the added reactant","the equilibrium remains completely unchanged","the reaction stops entirely"],"answer":1,"exp":"Increasing the concentration of a reactant shifts the equilibrium toward the products, as the system responds by consuming some of the additional reactant to counteract the change."},{"id":"src122007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For an exothermic reaction at equilibrium, what happens if the temperature is increased, according to Le Chatelier's Principle?","options":["the equilibrium shifts toward the products, favouring the exothermic (forward) direction","the equilibrium shifts toward the reactants, favouring the endothermic (reverse) direction, to absorb the added heat","temperature has no effect on equilibrium position","the reaction stops completely at higher temperatures"],"answer":1,"exp":"For an exothermic reaction, increasing the temperature shifts the equilibrium toward the reactants (the endothermic, reverse direction), as the system responds by favouring the direction that absorbs the added heat."},{"id":"src122008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For a reaction involving gases where the forward direction produces fewer moles of gas than the reactants, what happens to the equilibrium if pressure is increased, according to Le Chatelier's Principle?","options":["the equilibrium shifts toward the side with more moles of gas","the equilibrium shifts toward the side with fewer moles of gas, reducing the overall volume","pressure changes have no effect on gas-phase equilibria","the reaction stops completely at higher pressure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Increasing pressure shifts a gas-phase equilibrium toward the side with fewer moles of gas, as the system responds by reducing its overall volume to partially counteract the pressure increase."},{"id":"src122009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Catalysts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes the effect of adding a catalyst to a system at equilibrium?","options":["it shifts the equilibrium toward the products","it shifts the equilibrium toward the reactants","it speeds up both the forward and reverse reactions equally, helping the system reach equilibrium faster without changing the equilibrium position","it has no effect on the rate of either reaction"],"answer":2,"exp":"A catalyst speeds up both the forward and reverse reactions equally, helping the system reach equilibrium more quickly, but it does not change the actual position of equilibrium (the value of Kc remains unchanged)."},{"id":"src122010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes the industrial significance of the Haber process for producing ammonia (N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃)?","options":["it has no industrial significance","it provides an industrially important method for producing ammonia, a key ingredient in fertilisers, by carefully balancing equilibrium conditions","ammonia produced this way cannot be used for any practical purpose","this reaction does not actually reach equilibrium"],"answer":1,"exp":"The Haber process provides an industrially important method for producing ammonia, a key ingredient in fertilisers, by carefully selecting conditions (temperature, pressure, catalyst) that balance reaction rate with a favourable equilibrium position."},{"id":"src122011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"In the Haber process, why is a compromise temperature typically used, rather than the lowest possible temperature (which would favour the exothermic forward reaction)?","options":["temperature has no real effect on this reaction","while lower temperatures favour a greater yield of ammonia at equilibrium, they also significantly slow the reaction rate, so a compromise balances yield against a practical reaction speed","higher temperatures always produce more ammonia","the Haber process does not actually involve any temperature considerations"],"answer":1,"exp":"While lower temperatures favour a greater equilibrium yield of ammonia (since the forward reaction is exothermic), they also significantly slow the reaction rate. A compromise temperature balances achieving a reasonable yield against maintaining a practical, economically viable reaction speed."},{"id":"src122012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"What does the term 'position of equilibrium' refer to?","options":["the physical location of a reaction vessel in a laboratory","the relative concentrations of reactants and products once a reaction has reached equilibrium","a synonym for reaction rate","a measurement that applies only to solid-state reactions"],"answer":1,"exp":"The 'position of equilibrium' refers to the relative concentrations of reactants and products once a reaction has reached equilibrium, indicating whether the reaction favours reactants or products."},{"id":"src122013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For the reaction N₂O₄ ⇌ 2NO₂, if [N₂O₄]=0.2 mol/L and [NO₂]=0.8 mol/L at equilibrium, what is Kc?","options":["0.8","1.6","3.2","4.0"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Kc = [NO₂]² ÷ [N₂O₄]. Step 2: (0.8)² ÷ 0.2 = 0.64 ÷ 0.2 = 3.2."},{"id":"src122014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes why removing a product from a reaction mixture at equilibrium causes the equilibrium to shift toward the products?","options":["removing a product has no effect on equilibrium","the system responds to the decreased product concentration by favouring the forward reaction, partially replacing what was removed","removing a product always stops the reaction completely","equilibrium can only shift in response to temperature changes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Removing a product decreases its concentration, and the system responds (according to Le Chatelier's Principle) by favouring the forward reaction, partially replacing the product that was removed."},{"id":"src122015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Why does a solid or pure liquid not appear in the equilibrium constant expression (Kc), even if it participates in the reaction?","options":["solids and pure liquids are never actually involved in equilibrium reactions","the concentration (or activity) of a pure solid or liquid is considered constant, so it is incorporated into the value of Kc itself rather than written explicitly","this is simply an arbitrary convention with no real chemical basis","Kc expressions only apply to liquid-phase reactions"],"answer":1,"exp":"The concentration (or activity) of a pure solid or liquid is considered essentially constant, so rather than being written explicitly in the Kc expression, it is effectively incorporated into the constant itself."},{"id":"src122016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes how the value of Kc changes if the temperature of a reaction is changed?","options":["Kc always remains exactly the same value at any temperature","Kc generally changes with temperature, since the position of equilibrium itself shifts in response to temperature changes","Kc only changes in response to pressure, never temperature","Kc is not actually related to equilibrium position at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Kc generally changes with temperature, since changing temperature shifts the position of equilibrium itself (as described by Le Chatelier's Principle), which is reflected in a different equilibrium constant value."},{"id":"src122017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For the reaction 2SO₂ + O₂ ⇌ 2SO₃, if [SO₂]=1 mol/L, [O₂]=2 mol/L, and [SO₃]=4 mol/L at equilibrium, what is Kc?","options":["4","8","16","32"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Kc = [SO₃]² ÷ ([SO₂]² × [O₂]). Step 2: 4² ÷ (1² × 2) = 16 ÷ 2 = 8."},{"id":"src122018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which of these scenarios would shift an equilibrium toward the reactants, according to Le Chatelier's Principle?","options":["increasing the concentration of a reactant","decreasing the concentration of a product","increasing the concentration of a product","adding a catalyst"],"answer":2,"exp":"Increasing the concentration of a product causes the system to respond by favouring the reverse reaction, shifting the equilibrium toward the reactants to partially consume the additional product."},{"id":"src122019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes the role of equilibrium concepts in understanding the carbonic acid/bicarbonate buffer system in human blood?","options":["this system has no connection to equilibrium chemistry","this system relies on a reversible equilibrium reaction to help maintain a stable blood pH despite small additions of acid or base","blood pH is always perfectly stable with no chemical explanation needed","this system only exists in a laboratory setting, not in the human body"],"answer":1,"exp":"The carbonic acid/bicarbonate buffer system relies on a reversible equilibrium reaction, allowing the blood to absorb small additions of acid or base while maintaining a relatively stable pH, illustrating equilibrium chemistry's biological importance."},{"id":"src122020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Why is it generally true that not all reversible reactions reach a 'useful' equilibrium position within a practical timeframe?","options":["all reversible reactions always reach equilibrium instantly","reaction rate and equilibrium position are different concepts — a reaction might have a favourable equilibrium position but reach it extremely slowly without a catalyst","equilibrium position has no connection to reaction rate at all","this statement is never actually true for any reaction"],"answer":1,"exp":"Reaction rate and equilibrium position are distinct concepts — a reaction might have a thermodynamically favourable equilibrium position (high Kc) but reach that position extremely slowly without a catalyst to speed up the process."},{"id":"src122021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"If Kc for a reaction is very small (much less than 1), what does this indicate about the equilibrium position?","options":["the reaction strongly favours the products","the reaction strongly favours the reactants, meaning very little product forms at equilibrium","the reaction has not started yet","Kc values smaller than 1 are not chemically possible"],"answer":1,"exp":"A very small Kc value indicates that, at equilibrium, the concentration of reactants is much greater than the concentration of products, meaning the reaction strongly favours the reactants and very little product actually forms."},{"id":"src122022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes why industrial processes often operate at conditions that are NOT exactly at the theoretically ideal equilibrium yield?","options":["industrial processes always operate at perfect theoretical equilibrium","practical factors like reaction rate, cost, and safety often require a compromise between maximum theoretical yield and a feasible, economical process","equilibrium concepts have no relevance to real industrial processes","maximum yield is always the only consideration in industrial chemistry"],"answer":1,"exp":"Practical factors like reaction rate, cost, energy use, and safety often require industrial processes to compromise between achieving the maximum theoretical equilibrium yield and maintaining a feasible, economically viable process."},{"id":"src122023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Equilibrium Constant","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"For the reaction A ⇌ B + C, if [A]=4 mol/L, [B]=2 mol/L, and [C]=1 mol/L at equilibrium, what is Kc?","options":["0.5","2","8","16"],"answer":0,"exp":"Step 1: Kc = [B][C] ÷ [A]. Step 2: (2 × 1) ÷ 4 = 2 ÷ 4 = 0.5."},{"id":"src122024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"Which best describes why equilibrium is described as 'dynamic' rather than 'static'?","options":["nothing is actually happening at the molecular level once equilibrium is reached","both the forward and reverse reactions continue happening continuously at the molecular level, even though overall concentrations appear constant","equilibrium only describes solid-state reactions","dynamic equilibrium means the reaction rate is constantly increasing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Equilibrium is 'dynamic' because both the forward and reverse reactions continue happening continuously at the molecular level — it is only the observable, macroscopic concentrations that appear constant, not the underlying molecular activity."},{"id":"src122025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Chemical Equilibrium — Le Chatelier's Principle","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C2","q":"A chemist adds an inert gas (one that does not react) to a gas-phase equilibrium system, at constant volume. What effect does this have on the equilibrium position?","options":["it always shifts the equilibrium toward the products","it always shifts the equilibrium toward the reactants","since the inert gas does not change the concentrations or partial pressures of the actual reacting species, it has no effect on the equilibrium position at constant volume","it immediately stops the reaction entirely"],"answer":2,"exp":"At constant volume, adding an inert gas does not change the concentrations or partial pressures of the actual reacting species, so it has no effect on the equilibrium position, even though the total pressure of the system increases."},{"id":"src123001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Definitions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"According to the Bronsted-Lowry definition, what is an acid?","options":["a substance that accepts a proton (H⁺)","a substance that donates a proton (H⁺)","a substance that accepts electrons only","a substance with a pH above 7"],"answer":1,"exp":"According to the Bronsted-Lowry definition, an acid is a proton (H⁺) donor, while a base is a proton acceptor."},{"id":"src123002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Definitions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"According to the Bronsted-Lowry definition, what is a base?","options":["a substance that donates a proton (H⁺)","a substance that accepts a proton (H⁺)","a substance with a pH below 7","a substance that always contains oxygen"],"answer":1,"exp":"According to the Bronsted-Lowry definition, a base is a proton (H⁺) acceptor."},{"id":"src123003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pH of a solution with a hydrogen ion concentration [H⁺] of 1 × 10⁻³ mol/L?","options":["2","3","4","10"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: pH = -log₁₀[H⁺]. Step 2: -log₁₀(1×10⁻³) = 3."},{"id":"src123004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pH of a solution with a hydrogen ion concentration [H⁺] of 1 × 10⁻⁵ mol/L?","options":["3","5","9","11"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: pH = -log₁₀[H⁺]. Step 2: -log₁₀(1×10⁻⁵) = 5."},{"id":"src123005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the hydrogen ion concentration [H⁺] of a solution with a pH of 4?","options":["4 mol/L","1 × 10⁻⁴ mol/L","1 × 10⁴ mol/L","0.4 mol/L"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: [H⁺] = 10⁻ᵖᴴ. Step 2: 10⁻⁴ = 1 × 10⁻⁴ mol/L."},{"id":"src123006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pOH of a solution with a pH of 3, given that pH + pOH = 14 at 25°C?","options":["3","11","14","17"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: pH + pOH = 14. Step 2: pOH = 14 - 3 = 11."},{"id":"src123007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pH of a 0.01 mol/L solution of HCl, a strong acid that fully dissociates?","options":["1","2","12","13"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Since HCl fully dissociates, [H⁺] = 0.01 mol/L. Step 2: pH = -log₁₀(0.01) = 2."},{"id":"src123008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pH of a 0.001 mol/L solution of NaOH, a strong base that fully dissociates?","options":["3","9","11","13"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: [OH⁻] = 0.001 mol/L, so pOH = -log₁₀(0.001) = 3. Step 2: pH = 14 - pOH = 14 - 3 = 11."},{"id":"src123009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Titration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What volume of 0.1 mol/L NaOH is required to exactly neutralise 20 mL of 0.2 mol/L HCl?","options":["10 mL","20 mL","40 mL","80 mL"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: Moles of HCl = 0.2 × 0.020 = 0.004 mol. Step 2: Since NaOH and HCl react 1:1, moles NaOH needed = 0.004 mol. Step 3: Volume = moles ÷ concentration = 0.004 ÷ 0.1 = 0.04 L = 40 mL."},{"id":"src123010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Titration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What volume of 0.05 mol/L NaOH is required to exactly neutralise 25 mL of 0.1 mol/L HCl?","options":["25 mL","50 mL","75 mL","100 mL"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Moles of HCl = 0.1 × 0.025 = 0.0025 mol. Step 2: Moles NaOH needed = 0.0025 mol (1:1 ratio). Step 3: Volume = 0.0025 ÷ 0.05 = 0.05 L = 50 mL."},{"id":"src123011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Strength","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"Which best describes the difference between a 'strong acid' and a 'weak acid'?","options":["strong acids always have a higher concentration than weak acids","a strong acid fully dissociates into ions in solution, while a weak acid only partially dissociates","weak acids cannot lower the pH of a solution at all","there is no real chemical difference between strong and weak acids"],"answer":1,"exp":"A strong acid fully dissociates into ions in solution, releasing all its available H⁺ ions, while a weak acid only partially dissociates, establishing an equilibrium between the dissociated ions and the undissociated acid molecules."},{"id":"src123012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Strength","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"Which of these is an example of a weak acid?","options":["hydrochloric acid (HCl)","sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄)","acetic acid (CH₃COOH)","nitric acid (HNO₃)"],"answer":2,"exp":"Acetic acid (found in vinegar) is a weak acid, only partially dissociating in water, unlike the other strong acids listed which fully dissociate."},{"id":"src123013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Strength","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"Why can two solutions with the same molar concentration of a strong acid and a weak acid have different pH values?","options":["concentration is unrelated to pH","the strong acid fully dissociates, producing a higher [H⁺] than the weak acid, which only partially dissociates at the same concentration","weak acids always have a higher [H⁺] than strong acids at the same concentration","this scenario is impossible — they must always have identical pH"],"answer":1,"exp":"At the same molar concentration, a strong acid fully dissociates, producing a higher [H⁺] (and therefore a lower pH) than a weak acid, which only partially dissociates, releasing fewer H⁺ ions into solution."},{"id":"src123014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Conjugate Pairs","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is a 'conjugate base', in the context of Bronsted-Lowry acid-base theory?","options":["the species formed when an acid donates a proton","a synonym for a strong base","a base that has gained an extra hydrogen ion","a substance unrelated to acid-base reactions"],"answer":0,"exp":"A conjugate base is the species formed when an acid donates a proton (H⁺) — for example, when HCl donates a proton, it forms Cl⁻, the conjugate base of HCl."},{"id":"src123015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Conjugate Pairs","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is a 'conjugate acid', in the context of Bronsted-Lowry acid-base theory?","options":["the species formed when a base accepts a proton","a synonym for a weak acid","an acid that has lost a proton","a substance unrelated to acid-base reactions"],"answer":0,"exp":"A conjugate acid is the species formed when a base accepts a proton (H⁺) — for example, when NH₃ accepts a proton, it forms NH₄⁺, the conjugate acid of NH₃."},{"id":"src123016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"Which best describes an 'amphoteric' (or amphiprotic) substance?","options":["a substance that can only ever act as an acid","a substance that can act as either an acid or a base, depending on the reaction it is involved in","a substance with no acid-base properties at all","a synonym for a strong base"],"answer":1,"exp":"An amphoteric (or amphiprotic) substance can act as either an acid or a base, depending on the specific reaction it is involved in — water is a common example."},{"id":"src123017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Indicators","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"Which best describes the purpose of an indicator, such as litmus or phenolphthalein, in acid-base chemistry?","options":["indicators have no real chemical function","indicators change colour at certain pH levels, providing a visual signal of a solution's approximate acidity or basicity","indicators always neutralise the solution they're added to","indicators can only be used in extremely concentrated solutions"],"answer":1,"exp":"An indicator changes colour at certain pH levels, providing a convenient visual signal of a solution's approximate acidity or basicity, often used to detect the endpoint of a titration."},{"id":"src123018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Titration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the 'equivalence point' in an acid-base titration?","options":["the point at which the indicator first changes colour, regardless of stoichiometry","the point at which the moles of acid and base added are stoichiometrically equal, according to the reaction equation","the very start of the titration, before any base has been added","a point that only exists for strong acid-strong base titrations"],"answer":1,"exp":"The equivalence point is the point in a titration at which the moles of acid and base added are stoichiometrically equal, according to the reaction's balanced equation — this may or may not exactly align with the indicator's colour change (the 'endpoint')."},{"id":"src123019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Titration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"For a strong acid-strong base titration, what is the pH at the equivalence point typically equal to?","options":["0","7","10","14"],"answer":1,"exp":"For a strong acid-strong base titration, the pH at the equivalence point is typically equal to 7 (neutral), since the resulting salt solution does not significantly affect the water's natural pH."},{"id":"src123020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Titration","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"For a weak acid-strong base titration, why is the pH at the equivalence point typically greater than 7?","options":["weak acids always produce a pH below 7 at the equivalence point","the conjugate base formed (from the weak acid) reacts with water, producing a slightly basic solution","weak acid titrations never reach an equivalence point","this scenario always produces a strongly acidic solution"],"answer":1,"exp":"In a weak acid-strong base titration, the conjugate base formed from the weak acid (now fully neutralised) reacts slightly with water, producing a solution that is mildly basic, giving an equivalence point pH greater than 7."},{"id":"src123021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pH of a solution with a hydrogen ion concentration [H⁺] of 1 × 10⁻⁹ mol/L?","options":["5","9","11","13"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: pH = -log₁₀[H⁺]. Step 2: -log₁₀(1×10⁻⁹) = 9."},{"id":"src123022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pOH of a solution with a pH of 9?","options":["3","5","9","12"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: pH + pOH = 14. Step 2: pOH = 14 - 9 = 5."},{"id":"src123023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Concepts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"Which best describes why pure water has a pH of 7 at 25°C, despite being neither an added acid nor an added base?","options":["water never undergoes any ionisation","water undergoes slight self-ionisation, producing equal, small concentrations of H⁺ and OH⁻ ions, resulting in a neutral pH","water is technically classified as a weak acid only","pH 7 only applies to solutions containing dissolved salts"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pure water undergoes slight self-ionisation (H₂O ⇌ H⁺ + OH⁻), producing equal, small concentrations of H⁺ and OH⁻ ions, which results in a neutral pH of 7 at 25°C."},{"id":"src123024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — Buffers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the molar mass-based concentration of a buffer solution designed to resist pH changes — which best describes a 'buffer'?","options":["a solution that has no resistance to pH change at all","a solution containing a weak acid/conjugate base pair (or weak base/conjugate acid pair) that resists significant pH changes when small amounts of acid or base are added","a synonym for any strong acid solution","a solution that can only exist at exactly pH 7"],"answer":1,"exp":"A buffer solution contains a weak acid and its conjugate base (or a weak base and its conjugate acid) in significant quantities, allowing it to resist significant pH changes when small amounts of additional acid or base are introduced."},{"id":"src123025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Acids and Bases — pH Calculations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C3","q":"What is the pH of a 0.0001 mol/L solution of HCl, a strong acid that fully dissociates?","options":["2","4","6","10"],"answer":1,"exp":"Step 1: Since HCl fully dissociates, [H⁺] = 0.0001 = 1×10⁻⁴ mol/L. Step 2: pH = -log₁₀(1×10⁻⁴) = 4."},{"id":"src124001","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is 'oxidation', in terms of electron transfer?","options":["the gain of electrons","the loss of electrons","the gain of protons","the loss of neutrons"],"answer":1,"exp":"Oxidation is defined as the loss of electrons by a substance, often remembered with the mnemonic 'OIL RIG' (Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain)."},{"id":"src124002","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is 'reduction', in terms of electron transfer?","options":["the loss of electrons","the gain of electrons","the loss of protons","the gain of neutrons"],"answer":1,"exp":"Reduction is defined as the gain of electrons by a substance, remembered with the mnemonic 'OIL RIG' (Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain)."},{"id":"src124003","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"In the reaction Zn + Cu²⁺ → Zn²⁺ + Cu, which species is oxidised?","options":["Zn","Cu²⁺","Zn²⁺","Cu"],"answer":0,"exp":"Zn loses electrons (going from Zn to Zn²⁺), so it is oxidised in this reaction."},{"id":"src124004","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"In the reaction Zn + Cu²⁺ → Zn²⁺ + Cu, which species is reduced?","options":["Zn","Cu²⁺","Zn²⁺","Cu only as a separate, unrelated process"],"answer":1,"exp":"Cu²⁺ gains electrons (going from Cu²⁺ to Cu), so it is reduced in this reaction."},{"id":"src124005","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is an 'oxidising agent'?","options":["a substance that is itself oxidised, donating electrons","a substance that causes another substance to be oxidised, by accepting electrons itself (and therefore being reduced)","a substance that has no role in redox reactions","a synonym for a reducing agent"],"answer":1,"exp":"An oxidising agent causes another substance to be oxidised by accepting electrons from it — in doing so, the oxidising agent itself is reduced."},{"id":"src124006","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is a 'reducing agent'?","options":["a substance that causes another substance to be reduced, by donating electrons to it (and therefore being oxidised itself)","a substance that accepts electrons and is itself reduced","a substance with no role in redox reactions","a synonym for an oxidising agent"],"answer":0,"exp":"A reducing agent causes another substance to be reduced by donating electrons to it — in doing so, the reducing agent itself is oxidised."},{"id":"src124007","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions — Oxidation Numbers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is an 'oxidation number' (or oxidation state)?","options":["the actual physical charge measured on an atom","a conventional value assigned to an atom in a compound, representing its hypothetical charge if all bonds were fully ionic","a value that only applies to noble gases","a synonym for atomic mass"],"answer":1,"exp":"An oxidation number is a conventional value assigned to an atom in a compound or ion, representing its hypothetical charge if all bonds to that atom were considered fully ionic — a useful bookkeeping tool for tracking electron transfer."},{"id":"src124008","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions — Oxidation Numbers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is the oxidation number of oxygen in most compounds (excluding peroxides and a few exceptions)?","options":["+2","+1","-1","-2"],"answer":3,"exp":"Oxygen typically has an oxidation number of -2 in most compounds, due to its high electronegativity and tendency to gain two electrons."},{"id":"src124009","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions — Oxidation Numbers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is the oxidation number of hydrogen in most compounds (excluding metal hydrides)?","options":["+1","-1","+2","0"],"answer":0,"exp":"Hydrogen typically has an oxidation number of +1 in most compounds, such as in water (H₂O) or hydrochloric acid (HCl)."},{"id":"src124010","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Galvanic Cells","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"In a galvanic (voltaic) cell, at which electrode does oxidation occur?","options":["the cathode","the anode","both electrodes simultaneously","neither electrode — oxidation occurs in the external wire"],"answer":1,"exp":"In a galvanic cell, oxidation occurs at the anode, where the species loses electrons that then travel through the external circuit to the cathode."},{"id":"src124011","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Galvanic Cells","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"In a galvanic (voltaic) cell, at which electrode does reduction occur?","options":["the anode","the cathode","both electrodes simultaneously","neither electrode — reduction occurs in the salt bridge"],"answer":1,"exp":"In a galvanic cell, reduction occurs at the cathode, where the species gains the electrons that travelled through the external circuit from the anode."},{"id":"src124012","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Galvanic Cells","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What is the function of a 'salt bridge' (or porous barrier) in a galvanic cell?","options":["it has no real function and is purely decorative","it allows ions to flow between the two half-cells, maintaining electrical neutrality without allowing the bulk solutions to mix freely","it generates the electrical current directly","it prevents any electron flow in the cell"],"answer":1,"exp":"A salt bridge allows ions to flow between the two half-cells, maintaining electrical neutrality in each half-cell as electrons flow through the external circuit, without allowing the bulk solutions to mix freely."},{"id":"src124013","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Cell Potential","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"A galvanic cell has a cathode with a standard electrode potential of +0.34 V and an anode with a standard electrode potential of -0.76 V. What is the overall standard cell potential?","options":["0.42 V","0.76 V","1.10 V","1.42 V"],"answer":2,"exp":"Step 1: E°cell = E°cathode - E°anode. Step 2: 0.34 - (-0.76) = 0.34 + 0.76 = 1.10 V."},{"id":"src124014","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Cell Potential","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"A galvanic cell has a cathode with a standard electrode potential of +0.80 V and an anode with a standard electrode potential of +0.34 V. What is the overall standard cell potential?","options":["0.46 V","0.80 V","1.14 V","1.34 V"],"answer":0,"exp":"Step 1: E°cell = E°cathode - E°anode. Step 2: 0.80 - 0.34 = 0.46 V."},{"id":"src124015","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Cell Potential","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"What does a positive standard cell potential (E°cell) generally indicate about a galvanic cell reaction?","options":["the reaction is non-spontaneous under standard conditions","the reaction is spontaneous under standard conditions, and the cell can do useful electrical work","the cell cannot function at all","cell potential has no connection to reaction spontaneity"],"answer":1,"exp":"A positive standard cell potential indicates that the overall reaction is spontaneous under standard conditions, meaning the galvanic cell can generate useful electrical energy."},{"id":"src124016","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Cell Types","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes the difference between a galvanic cell and an electrolytic cell?","options":["a galvanic cell uses a spontaneous reaction to generate electrical energy, while an electrolytic cell uses an external electrical energy source to drive a non-spontaneous reaction","galvanic and electrolytic cells are identical in every way","an electrolytic cell always generates more energy than a galvanic cell","galvanic cells require an external power source, while electrolytic cells do not"],"answer":0,"exp":"A galvanic cell uses a spontaneous redox reaction to generate electrical energy, while an electrolytic cell uses an external electrical energy source to drive a non-spontaneous reaction forward."},{"id":"src124017","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Electrolysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes 'electrolysis'?","options":["a spontaneous chemical reaction occurring with no outside energy input","the process of using electrical energy to drive a non-spontaneous chemical reaction, such as decomposing a compound","a synonym for combustion","a process that only occurs in gases"],"answer":1,"exp":"Electrolysis is the process of using electrical energy from an external source to drive a non-spontaneous chemical reaction, such as decomposing water into hydrogen and oxygen gas."},{"id":"src124018","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Electrolysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"In an electrolytic cell, which electrode is connected to the negative terminal of the external power source, and what occurs there?","options":["the anode; oxidation occurs there","the cathode; reduction occurs there","the cathode; oxidation occurs there","the anode; reduction occurs there"],"answer":1,"exp":"In an electrolytic cell, the cathode is connected to the negative terminal of the external power source, and reduction occurs there, as electrons are forced into this electrode and onto the species being reduced."},{"id":"src124019","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes why metals like sodium and aluminium are extracted using electrolysis, rather than simpler chemical reduction methods?","options":["electrolysis is never actually used in industrial metal extraction","these metals are highly reactive, and a stronger driving force (electrical energy) is needed to reduce their ions back to the metal, since few chemical reducing agents are strong enough","sodium and aluminium do not actually form ionic compounds","electrolysis is always cheaper than chemical reduction for every metal"],"answer":1,"exp":"Highly reactive metals like sodium and aluminium require a stronger driving force than most chemical reducing agents can provide, making electrolysis (using electrical energy) necessary to reduce their ions back into pure metal."},{"id":"src124020","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes corrosion (such as the rusting of iron) in terms of redox chemistry?","options":["corrosion involves no electron transfer at all","corrosion is an oxidation process, where the metal loses electrons and reacts with substances like oxygen and water in the environment","corrosion only occurs in a vacuum, with no surrounding substances involved","corrosion is purely a physical process, unrelated to chemistry"],"answer":1,"exp":"Corrosion, such as the rusting of iron, is fundamentally an oxidation process, where the metal loses electrons and reacts with environmental substances like oxygen and water to form oxide compounds."},{"id":"src124021","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes how 'sacrificial protection' (such as zinc coating on iron, known as galvanising) helps prevent corrosion?","options":["the zinc coating has no real protective function","the more reactive zinc is preferentially oxidised instead of the iron, protecting the iron as long as the zinc coating remains","zinc coating makes iron impossible to oxidise under any circumstances","sacrificial protection works by preventing all contact between iron and oxygen, with no chemical mechanism involved"],"answer":1,"exp":"In sacrificial protection, the more reactive zinc is preferentially oxidised instead of the less reactive iron, since zinc more readily loses electrons — this protects the iron for as long as a sufficient zinc coating remains."},{"id":"src124022","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Cell Potential","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"A galvanic cell has a cathode with a standard electrode potential of -0.13 V and an anode with a standard electrode potential of -0.76 V. What is the overall standard cell potential?","options":["0.63 V","0.76 V","0.89 V","-0.63 V"],"answer":0,"exp":"Step 1: E°cell = E°cathode - E°anode. Step 2: -0.13 - (-0.76) = -0.13 + 0.76 = 0.63 V."},{"id":"src124023","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Cell Potential","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes the relationship between a species' standard electrode potential and its tendency to be reduced?","options":["a more positive standard electrode potential indicates a greater tendency to be reduced (gain electrons)","a more positive standard electrode potential indicates a greater tendency to be oxidised","standard electrode potential has no connection to a species' tendency to be reduced or oxidised","all species have an identical tendency to be reduced, regardless of their potential"],"answer":0,"exp":"A more positive standard electrode potential indicates a greater tendency for that species to be reduced (gain electrons), which is why species with high (positive) electrode potentials tend to act as oxidising agents."},{"id":"src124024","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Redox Reactions — Balancing Equations","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes the balancing requirement for a redox equation, in terms of electrons transferred?","options":["electrons do not need to be balanced in redox equations","the number of electrons lost during oxidation must equal the number of electrons gained during reduction","only atoms need to be balanced, not electrons","redox equations can never actually be balanced"],"answer":1,"exp":"In a balanced redox equation, the number of electrons lost during the oxidation half-reaction must equal the number of electrons gained during the reduction half-reaction, ensuring no electrons are created or destroyed overall."},{"id":"src124025","state":"AU","section":"sr_chemistry","grade":"12","topic":"Electrochemistry — Applications","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G12-C4","q":"Which best describes why batteries (such as those in a torch or phone) are practical applications of galvanic cells?","options":["batteries have no connection to galvanic cell chemistry","batteries use spontaneous redox reactions occurring within the battery to generate a usable electrical current","batteries always require electrolysis to function","batteries generate energy without any chemical reaction occurring"],"answer":1,"exp":"Batteries are practical applications of galvanic cells, using spontaneous redox reactions occurring within sealed compartments to generate a usable electrical current for portable devices."},{"q":"What is 'molar mass'?","options":["The mass of one atom","The mass of one mole of a substance (g/mol), numerically equal to its relative atomic/molecular mass","The density of a substance","The mass of one molecule"],"answer":1,"topic":"Chemistry","exp":"Molar mass: 12 g/mol for carbon (Ar=12), 18 g/mol for water (2+16). n=m/M. 1 mole contains 6.02×10²³ particles (Avogadro's number).","difficulty":"medium","id":"srcF60000034","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'Le Chatelier's Principle'?","options":["Reactions always go to completion","When a system at equilibrium is disturbed, it shifts to partially counteract the disturbance","Temperature always increases in reactions","All reversible reactions reach completion"],"answer":1,"topic":"Equilibrium","exp":"Add reactant → equilibrium shifts right (forward). Remove product → shifts right. Increase pressure → shifts toward fewer moles of gas. Increase temperature → shifts endothermic.","difficulty":"hard","id":"srcF60000035","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"What is the 'octet rule'?","options":["Atoms always have 8 protons","Atoms tend to gain, lose or share electrons to achieve 8 electrons in their outer shell","Only elements with 8 electrons react","Carbon always forms 8 bonds"],"answer":1,"topic":"Chemical Bonding","exp":"Octet rule drives bonding: NaCl (Na gives electron to Cl — both get 8 outer electrons). Exceptions: H (needs 2), B (often 6), P and S (can have expanded octets).","difficulty":"medium","id":"srcF60000036","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"What is an 'exothermic reaction'?","options":["Absorbs heat","Releases heat to surroundings (ΔH is negative)","Only occurs at high temperatures","Requires a catalyst"],"answer":1,"topic":"Thermochemistry","exp":"Exothermic: bonds formed > bonds broken. ΔH<0. Examples: combustion, neutralisation, respiration. Endothermic: ΔH>0 (photosynthesis, melting, electrolysis).","difficulty":"medium","id":"srcF60000037","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"What distinguishes an acid from a base (Brønsted-Lowry definition)?","options":["Acids are red","Acids are proton (H⁺) donors; bases are proton acceptors","Acids turn litmus blue","Bases release OH⁻ only"],"answer":1,"topic":"Acids & Bases","exp":"Brønsted-Lowry: more general than Arrhenius. HCl (acid) donates H⁺ to NH₃ (base) → Cl⁻ + NH₄⁺. Amphiprotic substances can act as either.","difficulty":"medium","id":"srcF60000038","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'empirical formula'?","options":["The exact molecular formula","The simplest whole-number ratio of atoms in a compound","The formula showing structural bonds","The 3D arrangement of atoms"],"answer":1,"topic":"Chemical Formulae","exp":"Empirical formula: glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆) → CH₂O. Benzene (C₆H₆) → CH. Used when the exact molecular formula is unknown or when simplest ratio is needed.","difficulty":"medium","id":"srcF60000039","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'titration' used for?","options":["Measuring temperature","Determining the unknown concentration of a solution using a solution of known concentration","Measuring pH","Separating mixtures"],"answer":1,"topic":"Analytical Chemistry","exp":"Titration: add standard solution (known conc.) to analyte (unknown) using a burette until equivalence point (indicator changes colour). Calculate concentration using n=cV.","difficulty":"medium","id":"srcF60000040","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"},{"q":"In a galvanic cell, where does oxidation occur?","options":["Cathode","At both electrodes","Anode","Neither electrode"],"answer":2,"topic":"Electrochemistry","exp":"Oxidation occurs at the anode; reduction at the cathode. Mnemonic: AN OX, RED CAT (anode/oxidation, cathode/reduction). Electrons flow anode→cathode through external circuit.","difficulty":"hard","id":"srcF60000041","section":"sr_chemistry","state":"VIC","grade":12,"style":"standard"}];